<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<worksheet>
  <title>21 - Singular Value Decomposition (Section 7.4)</title>
  <objectives>
    <introduction>
      <p>Make sure you can answer the following:</p>
    </introduction>
    <ul>
      <li><p>How are the singular values of <m>A</m> related to the eigenvalues of <m>G=A^TA</m>?  How are the right singular vectors of <m>A</m> related to the eigenvectors of <m>G</m>.</p></li>
      <li><p>How can you find the left singular vectors of <m>A</m>?</p></li>
      <li><p>How can you build the singular value decompostition for any matrix <m>A</m>?</p></li>
    </ul>
  </objectives>
  <introduction>
    <p><term>MTH 205</term></p>
    <p>There will always be a page of Sage cells at <url href="https://gvsu.edu/s/0Ng">gvsu.edu/s/0Ng</url>.</p>
    <p>Given any matrix <m>A</m>, we now want to study the function <m>f(\xvec) = |A\xvec|</m>, which is not a
quadratic form. For example, if <m>A=\mattwo{2}{0}{0}{-1}</m> then <m>f\left(\twovec{x_1}{x_2}\right)=\sqrt{4x_1^2+x_2^2}</m>.</p>
    <p>While <m>f(x)</m> is not a quadratic form, it becomes one if we square it!  That is, 
<md>(f(\xvec))^2 = |A\xvec|^2 = (A\xvec)\cdot (A\xvec) = \xvec \cdot (A^TA\xvec) = q_{A^TA}(\xvec).</md></p>
    <p>Let <m>G = A^TA</m>; we call <m>G</m> the "Gram matrix" associated with <m>A</m>.  Note that <m>f(\xvec) = \sqrt{q_G(\xvec)}</m>.</p>
    <p>You will find a figure at <url href="https://gvsu.edu/s/0YE">gvsu.edu/s/0YE</url> ("zero Y E") that allows you to select a matrix
<m>A</m> and vary the red vector <m>\xvec</m> on the left. You will see the vector <m>A\xvec</m> on the right. The height
of the blue rectangle shows you the value of <m>f(\xvec) = |A\xvec|</m>.</p>
  </introduction>

  <exercise>
    <introduction>
      <p>Let’s start with <m>A =\mattwo{1}{2}{-2}{-1}</m>, which is NOT symmetric.</p>
    </introduction>
    <task workspace="1in">
      <statement>
        <p>The first <term>singular value</term> <m>\sigma_1</m>
 is the maximum value of <m>f(\xvec)</m>
 over all unit vectors and an associated <term>right singular vector</term> <m>\vvec_1</m>
 is a unit vector describing a direction in which this maximum occurs.
Use the diagram to find the first singular value <m>\sigma_1</m>
 and an associated right singular vector <m>\vvec_1</m>.</p>
      </statement>
    </task>
    <task workspace="1in">
      <statement>
        <p>The second <term>singular value</term> <m>\sigma_2</m>
 is the minimum value of <m>f(\xvec)</m>
 over all unit vectors and an associated <term>right singular vector</term> <m>\vvec_2</m>
 is a unit vector describing a direction in which this minimum occurs.
Use the diagram to find the second singular value <m>\sigma_2</m>
 and an associated right singular vector <m>\vvec_2</m>.</p>
      </statement>
    </task>
    <task workspace="1in">
      <statement>
        <p>Without using the diagram:  Remember <m>f(\xvec) = \sqrt{q_G(\xvec)}</m> with <m>G=A^TA</m>.  Since <m>G</m> is symmetric, it is orthogonally diagonalizable.  Find <m>G</m> and an orthogonal diagonalization of it.</p>
      </statement>
    </task>
    <task workspace="1in">
      <statement>
        <p>What is the maximum value of the quadratic form <m>q_G(\xvec)</m>
 among all unit vectors and in which direction does it occur? What is the minimum value of <m>q_G(\xvec)</m>
 and in which direction does it occur?</p>
      </statement>
    </task>
    <task workspace="1in">
      <statement>
        <p>What is the relationship between the eigenvalues of <m>G</m> and the singular values of <m>A</m>?  (Recall <m>f(\xvec)=\sqrt{q_G(\xvec)}</m>.)</p>
      </statement>
    </task>
    <task workspace="1in">
      <statement>
        <p>What is the relationship between the eigenvectors of the symmetric matrix <m>G</m> and the right singular vectors <m>\vvec_1</m> and <m>\vvec_2</m> of <m>A</m>?</p>
      </statement>
    </task>
    <task workspace="1in">
      <statement>
        <p>Can we form an orthonormal basis from <m>\vvec_1</m> and <m>\vvec_2</m>?  How do we know? (Recall, <m>G</m> is symmetric...)</p>
      </statement>
    </task>
    <task workspace="1in">
      <statement>
        <p>Let's introduce something new.  We have <m>\vvec_1</m> and <m>\vvec_2</m> which are the <term>right singular vectors</term>.  The <term>left singular vectors</term> <m>\uvec_1</m> and <m>\uvec_2</m> are found from <m>A\vvec_1 = \sigma_1\uvec_1</m> and <m>A\vvec_2 = \sigma_2\uvec_2</m>. (That is, they are unit vectors that point in the direction <m>A\vvec_i</m>) Find the two left singular vectors, <m>\uvec_1</m> and <m>\uvec_2</m>.</p>
      </statement>
    </task>
    <task workspace="1in">
      <statement>
        <p>Why are <m>\uvec_1</m> and <m>\uvec_2</m> unit vectors?  Hint: we know <m>f(\vvec_i)=|A\vvec_i| = \sigma_i</m>.</p>
      </statement>
    </task>
    <task workspace="1in">
      <statement>
        <p>Form the matrices:
<md>U = \left[ \uvec_1 \ \ \uvec_2\right], \ \ \ \Sigma = \mattwo{\sigma_1}{0}{0}{\sigma_2}, \ \ \ V = \left[\vvec_1 \ \ \vvec_2\right]</md></p>
      </statement>
    </task>
    <task workspace="1in">
      <statement>
        <p>Explain why <m>AV = U\Sigma</m>.  (<m>\Sigma</m> is the Greek letter "Sigma").</p>
      </statement>
    </task>
    <task workspace="2cm">
      <statement>
        <p>Is <m>V</m> an orthogonal matrix (i.e. does it have orthonormal columns)? Then what is the relationship between <m>V^T</m> and <m>V^{-1}</m>?</p>
      </statement>
    </task>
    <task workspace="1in">
      <statement>
        <p>Explain why this leads to <m>A=U\Sigma V^T</m>, and verify this relationship holds for this example.</p>
      </statement>
    </task>
    <conclusion>
      <p>Putting all this together, we have  <term>singular value decomposition</term> of a matrix <m>A</m>:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><p>Construct the Gram matrix <m>G=A^TA</m>, and find an orthogonal diagonalization to find eigenvalues <m>\lambda_i</m> with corresponding orthonormal basis of eigenvectors <m>\vvec_i</m>.</p></li>
        <li><p>The singular values of <m>A</m> are <m>\sigma_i = \sqrt{\lambda_i}</m>.  By convention, they are listed in decreasing order:  <m>\sigma_1 \ge \sigma_2 \ge \ldots</m>.  The right singular vectors are the <m>\vvec_i</m>.</p></li>
        <li><p>The left singular vectors <m>\uvec_i</m> are found from <m>A\vvec_i = \sigma_i\uvec_i</m>, where <m>\uvec_i</m> are also unit vectors.  (They also form an orthonormal basis!)</p></li>
      </ul>
    </conclusion>
  </exercise>

  <exercise>
    <introduction>
      <p>Consider <m>A = \left[\begin{array}{rrr}
     1\amp0\amp-1  \\
     1\amp1\amp1 
\end{array}\right]</m>.  (Not square!  No eigenvalues!)</p>
    </introduction>
    <task workspace="1in">
      <statement>
        <p>Construct the Gram matrix <m>G=A^TA</m> and find it's orthogonal diagonalization.</p>
      </statement>
    </task>
    <task workspace="1in">
      <statement>
        <p>In building the singular value decomposition, the matrices <m>U</m> and <m>V</m> will always be
orthogonal matrices so they must be square. The matrix <m>\Sigma</m> will always have the
same shape as <m>A</m>; in this case, <m>\Sigma</m> will be <m>2\times 3</m>. Find the singular values <m>\sigma_1</m> and <m>\sigma_2</m> of
<m>A</m> and form <m>\Sigma = \left[\begin{array}{rrr}
     \sigma_1\amp0\amp0  \\
     0\amp\sigma_2\amp0 
\end{array}\right]</m>.</p>
      </statement>
    </task>
    <task workspace="1in">
      <statement>
        <p>Identify three right singular vectors <m>\vvec_1</m>, <m>\vvec_2</m>, and <m>\vvec_3</m> and form the matrix <m>V</m> having
these vectors as its columns.</p>
      </statement>
    </task>
    <task workspace="1in">
      <statement>
        <p>We now need to form the left singular vectors. If we want <m>A = U\Sigma V^T</m>, then the
matrix product <m>U\Sigma</m> needs to make sense. This means that the number of columns of
<m>U</m> equals the number of rows of <m>\Sigma</m>, which is 2. Therefore <m>U</m> should be a <m>2\times 2</m> matrix.
Find left singular vectors using <m>A\vvec_i = \sigma_i\uvec_i</m>.</p>
      </statement>
    </task>
    <task workspace="1in">
      <statement>
        <p>Form the matrix <m>U =\left[\uvec_1 \ \  \uvec_2\right]</m>. Then verify that <m>A=U\Sigma V^T</m>.</p>
      </statement>
    </task>
    <task workspace="1in">
      <statement>
        <p>How can you use this singular value decomposition of <m>A</m>
 to easily find a singular value decomposition of <m>A^T=\left[\begin{array}{rr}
      1\amp1  \\
      0\amp1\\ -1\amp1 
 \end{array}\right]</m>.</p>
      </statement>
    </task>
  </exercise>

  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>(If time): Find the singular value decomposition for <m>A=\left[\begin{array}{rrr}
     2\amp-2\amp1  \\
     -4\amp-8 \amp-8
\end{array}\right]</m> and verify that <m>A=U\Sigma V^T</m>.</p>
    </statement>
  </exercise>

</worksheet>
